        "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
        "score": 0,
        "is_accepted": false,
        "last_activity_date": 1400689588,
        "creation_date": 1400689098,
        "body": "<p>Your question is confusing and should be rewritten.<\/p>\n\n<p>No need to call currentTimeMillis as DateTime does that by default.<\/p>\n\n<p>No need to call toLocalDateTime. That would be used when you want to lose time zone, but you are already in UTC so no time zone applies so no need to drop time zone.<\/p>\n\n<p>You are working too hard with the println lines calculating sec, minutes, hours. The <a href=\"http://www.joda.org/joda-time/apidocs/org/joda/time/field/StrictDateTimeField.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>PeriodFormatterBuilder<\/code><\/a> class performs such work.<\/p>\n\n<p>You need to be clear about java.util.Date and java.sql.Date. The latter sets the time portion to zeros. Neither has a time zone. Be aware of a third type bundled with Java, <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/Timestamp.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">java.sql.Timestamp<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>When debugging and posting this kind of question, get the milliseconds that back the Date and DateTime objects so we have accurate data. In my usual work I avoid using or thinking in milliseconds, but for debugging it can be useful.<\/p>\n\n<p>As Jon Skeet said, you should store date-time values as date-time types in your database rather than strings. <\/p>\n\n<p>I suggest you search StackOverflow for many similar questions providing example code.<\/p>\n",
